article.headline: San Francisco 74, Delaware 72
article.story: NEWARK, Del. (AP) -- Andre Hazel hit a fadeaway jumper in the lane just before the buzzer to give San Francisco a 74-72 victory over Delaware on Sunday. Hazel finished with 14 points, and Tyrone Riley scored 15 and had a game-high 10 rebounds. Riley hit three clutch three pointers in the final three minutes for the Dons (3-3). Delaware (2-1) failed to start 3-0 for the first time in four years and lost its home opener for the first time in six seasons. Mike Ames scored 14 points to lead the Blue Hens. Robin Wentt scored 12, and David Lunn contributed 11. The game featured 16 ties and was close throughout, with neither team building a lead larger than six points. With the score tied at 69 with 26 seconds remaining, Riley gathered up a loose ball and hit a 3-pointer from the left wing as the shot clock expired. Lunn followed with a 3-pionter to tie it at 72 with 15 seconds left. Following a San Francisco timeout, Hazel penetrated and hit the winning shot from the left side of the lane. Delaware led 33-29 at halftime before San Francisco tied it at 44 with 14:19 left. The Blue Hens took a 67-63 lead on a layup by Wentt with 3:23 remaining. Riley then hit two 3-pointers within a minute to give the Dons a 69-67 lead with 2:01 left. San Francisco went 8-for-10 from three-point range and 14-of-18 from the free-throw line. Delaware hit just 15-of-24 from the foul line, including 9-of-16 in the second half.
